         <abstract>
            <p>Let r(x) be the product of all distinct primes dividing a nonzero integer x. The abc-conjecture says that if a, b, c are nonzero relatively prime integers such that a + b + c = 0, then the biggest limit point of the numbers log max(|a|, |b|, |c|)/log r(abc) equals 1. We show that in a natural analogue of this conjecture for n ≥ 3 integers, the largest limit point should be replaced by at least 2n - 5. We present an algorithm leading to numerous examples of triples a, b, c for which the above quotients strongly deviate from the conjectural value 1.</p>
          </abstract>
